"Gamo T.","Dissolved oxygen in the bottom water of the Sea of Japan as a sensitive alarm for global climate change",2011,"TrAC - Trends in Analytical Chemistry","30","8",,"1308","1319",,,10.1016/j.trac.2011.06.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052280707&partnerID=40&md5=b6699e6c055690bcbb52eeba182fe9fd","Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute, The University of Tokyo, 5-1-5, Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8564, Japan","Gamo, T., Atmosphere and Ocean Research Institute, The University of Tokyo, 5-1-5, Kashiwanoha, Kashiwa, Chiba 277-8564, Japan","The Sea of Japan, a semi-closed marginal sea (greatest depth ~3700m) in the northwestern-most Pacific Ocean, has an independent, deep convection system, which is driven by the formation and the sinking of cool, saline surface water towards the bottom in severe winters. Continuous measurement of dissolved oxygen using highly precise versions of the Winkler titration method has revealed 8-10% decreases in the bottom concentration of oxygen (O2) over the past 30years. The temporal decrease in O2 means an imbalance between the supply of O2 from the surface and the in situ consumption of O2 in decomposing organic matter, suggesting that the change in the deep convection pattern of the Sea of Japan is probably caused by global climate change to reduce winter cooling of surface seawater. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.","Abyssal circulation; Bottom water; Chemical oceanography; Dissolved oxygen; Global warming; Long-term monitoring; Sea of Japan; Seawater; Winkler titration; Winter cooling","Abyssal circulation; Bottom water; Chemical oceanography; Long term monitoring; Sea of Japan; Winkler; Winter cooling; Biochemical oxygen demand; Dissolution; Global warming; Natural convection; Oceanography; Seawater; Titration; Dissolved oxygen; chlorofluorocarbon; dissolved oxygen; radium 226; sea water; tracer; tritium; amperometry; climate change; deep sea; environmental change; geography; greenhouse effect; Japan; oceanogra